    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-12-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-12-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="153"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                <head>153. Letter From Acting Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_KNB1"
                        type="from">Katzenbach</persName> to Secretary of Defense <persName
                        corresp="#p_MNRS1" type="to">McNamara</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d153fn1">Source: Washington National Records
                        Center, OASD/<gloss target="#t_ISA1">ISA</gloss> Files: <gloss
                            target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 330 70 A 6648, 384 1966 Jan-.
                        Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-12-08">December 8, 1966</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Dear Bob:</p>
                <p>Thank you for your letter of November 17 transmitting a Defense draft <gloss
                        target="#t_NSAM1">NSAM</gloss> on chemical and biological warfare
                        policy.<note n="2" xml:id="d153fn2">
                        <ref target="#d145">Document 145</ref>.</note> Our initial reaction is that
                    there are large areas of agreement between your draft and the <gloss
                        target="#t_CB1">CB</gloss> paper developed in State<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d153fn3">See <ref target="#d145fn3">footnote 3, Document
                        145</ref>.</note> and previously sent to Defense and other interested
                    agencies. Both drafts are now being studied by members of my staff. After
                    completion of this work, it may be useful to follow up on your suggestion to
                    discuss any remaining issues. You will recall that <persName>Bill
                        Foster</persName> stressed the desirability for developing basic national
                    policy in the <gloss target="#t_CB1">CB</gloss> field in a letter to the
                    Committee of Principals in October, 1963.<note n="4" xml:id="d153fn4">See <ref
                            target="#d121fn2">footnote 2, Document 121</ref>.</note> More recently,
                    on April 19, 1966, Butch <persName corresp="#p_FAS2">Fisher</persName> addressed
                    a letter on the same subject to the Deputies.<note n="5" xml:id="d153fn5">
                        <ref target="#d122">Document 122</ref>.</note> In view of <gloss
                        target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>’s continuing interest in our <gloss
                        target="#t_CB1">CB</gloss> policy, I suggest that it would be desirable to
                    invite Bill, as well as <persName>Dick Helms</persName> and Len Marks, to join
                    the discussions. I will subsequently be in touch with you about a mutually
                    agreeable time.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Nick</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
